{"title_page": "Hair gel", "text_new": "[[Image:Hair gel.jpg|thumb|Short Hair styled with hair gel]]\n'''Hair gel''' is a [[hairstyling product]] that is used to harden  [[hair]] into a particular [[hairstyle]].\n\n==History==\n\nAnalysis of [[ancient Egypt]]ian mummies has shown that they styled their hair using a [[fat]]-based [[gel]]. The researchers behind the analysis say that the Egyptians used the product to ensure that their style stayed in place in both life and death. Natalie McCreesh, an archaeological scientist from the KNH Centre for Biomedical Egyptology at the [[University of Manchester]], England, and her colleagues studied hair samples taken from 18 mummies. The oldest is approximately 3,500 years old, but most were excavated from a cemetery in the Dakhleh Oasis in the [[Libyan Desert|Western Desert]] and date from [[Greco-Roman]] times, around 2,300 years ago.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Marchant, Jo|journal=Journal of Archaeological Science |volume =38|issue= 12|date=December 2011|pages =3432-3434|title=Ancient Egyptians used 'hair gel': Mummy analysis finds that fat-based product held styles in place.|lay-url=http://www.nature.com/news/2011/110819/full/news.2011.487.html |laysource=Nature News| doi = 10.1016/j.jas.2011.08.004}}</ref>\n\nThe Irish [[bog body]] [[Clonycavan Man]], which has been [[radiocarbon dating|radiocarbon dated]] to between 392 BC and 201 BC, was found to have been using a hair gel made from pine tree resin imported from\nSpain or South-west France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irisharchaeology.ie/2011/08/irish-bog-bodies-recent-discoveries/|website=Irish Archaeology|title=Irish bog bodies, some recent discoveries|author= Colm |date= August 11, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1914, in a small pharmacy located in the heart of Buenos Aires, Argentina (Florida at 600), veterinary student Jos\u00e9 Antonio Brancato created the first fixative for hair, which would carry the name gomina as a registered trademark. For this, he mixed gum Arabic, Persian tragacanth and different essences. Soon the word \"gomina\" became synonymous with fixative. A fixative that displaced the soaps and oils used for this purpose.\n\nIn 1929, the British company Chemico Works invented [[Brylcreem]], which became the market leader among hair styling products in both the U.K. and the U.S. during the following decades.\n\nIn the 1960s, modern hair gel was invented in the United States, by what would later be renamed the Dep Corporation. Marketed under the brand name Dep, modern hair gel was given this name by its inventor, Luis Montoya, in recognition of the substance that gave it its unique, non-greasy consistency: [[diethyl phthalate]], commonly abbreviated as DEP.{{cn|date=December 2015}}\n\n==Types==\n[[File:Dollop of hair gel.jpg|thumb|A dollop of hair gel.]]\n\nMany brands of hair [[gel]] in North America and the UK come in numbered variants. Higher numbered gels maintain a greater \"hold\" on hair, while lower numbers do not make the hair as stiff and in some products give the hair a wet look. A category typically referred to as \"ethnic\" gels is designed and manufactured specifically for sculpting the hair texture common to [[African Americans]]. [[Mediterranean]]s, [[Eastern Europeans]], and [[Latin American]]s are also ethnic groups who are known for using [https://habsell.in/how-to-increase-the-hair-gel-from-home-due-to-lockdown/ hair gel].\n\nSome forms of hair gel are marketed to consumers who want to \"spike\" their hair in the style that emerged from the [[hardcore punk]] subculture in the 1980s. Some hair gels include temporary [[Hair colouring|hair coloring]], which includes variants in unnatural colors associated with various [[subculture]]s, such as the [[Gothic fashion|goth]]s, [[rave]]rs, [[mobster]]s, and [[greaser (subculture)|greasers]].\n\n===Cationic polymers===\n[[Cation]]ic [[polymer]]s are among the main functional components of hair gel. The positive charges in the polymers causes them to stretch, making the gel more [[viscosity|viscous]]. Hair gels resist natural protein conformations and allow hair to be styled and textured, because the stretched-out polymer takes up more space than a coiled polymer and thus resists the flow of solvent molecules around it. The positive charges also bind the gel to the negatively charged [[amino acid]]s on the surface of the [[keratin]] molecules in the hair.{{cn|date=December 2015}} \n\n=== Other polymers ===\nMore complicated polymer formulas exist; i.e., a [[copolymer]] of [[vinylpyrrolidone]], [[methacrylamide]], and [[N-vinylimidazole]].{{cn|date=December 2015}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hair mousse]]\n*[[Hair wax]]\n*[[Pomade]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.bigredtoybox.com/cgi-bin/toynfo.pl?dippitydooindex|work=GoGoMag |publisher=Big Red Toybox: The Vintage Toy Encyclopedia|title=Dippity-do Setting Gel by Gillette|author=Summer Storm}}\n\n{{cosmetics}}\n[[Category:Hairdressing]]\n\n[[bn:\u09b9\u09c7\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09b0 \u099c\u09c7\u09b2]]\n[[ja:\u6574\u9aea\u6599#\u30d8\u30a2\u30b8\u30a7\u30eb]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Hair gel.jpg|thumb|Short Hair styled with hair gel]]\n'''Hair gel''' is a [[hairstyling product]] that is used to harden  [[hair]] into a particular [[hairstyle]].\n\n==History==\n\nAnalysis of [[ancient Egypt]]ian mummies has shown that they styled their hair using a [[fat]]-based [[gel]]. The researchers behind the analysis say that the Egyptians used the product to ensure that their style stayed in place in both life and death. Natalie McCreesh, an archaeological scientist from the KNH Centre for Biomedical Egyptology at the [[University of Manchester]], England, and her colleagues studied hair samples taken from 18 mummies. The oldest is approximately 3,500 years old, but most were excavated from a cemetery in the Dakhleh Oasis in the [[Libyan Desert|Western Desert]] and date from [[Greco-Roman]] times, around 2,300 years ago.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Marchant, Jo|journal=Journal of Archaeological Science |volume =38|issue= 12|date=December 2011|pages =3432-3434|title=Ancient Egyptians used 'hair gel': Mummy analysis finds that fat-based product held styles in place.|lay-url=http://www.nature.com/news/2011/110819/full/news.2011.487.html |laysource=Nature News| doi = 10.1016/j.jas.2011.08.004}}</ref>\n\nThe Irish [[bog body]] [[Clonycavan Man]], which has been [[radiocarbon dating|radiocarbon dated]] to between 392 BC and 201 BC, was found to have been using a hair gel made from pine tree resin imported from\nSpain or South-west France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irisharchaeology.ie/2011/08/irish-bog-bodies-recent-discoveries/|website=Irish Archaeology|title=Irish bog bodies, some recent discoveries|author= Colm |date= August 11, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1914, in a small pharmacy located in the heart of Buenos Aires, Argentina (Florida at 600), veterinary student Jos\u00e9 Antonio Brancato created the first fixative for hair, which would carry the name gomina as a registered trademark. For this, he mixed gum Arabic, Persian tragacanth and different essences. Soon the word \"gomina\" became synonymous with fixative. A fixative that displaced the soaps and oils used for this purpose.\n\nIn 1929, the British company Chemico Works invented [[Brylcreem]], which became the market leader among hair styling products in both the U.K. and the U.S. during the following decades.\n\nIn the 1960s, modern hair gel was invented in the United States, by what would later be renamed the Dep Corporation. Marketed under the brand name Dep, modern hair gel was given this name by its inventor, Luis Montoya, in recognition of the substance that gave it its unique, non-greasy consistency: [[diethyl phthalate]], commonly abbreviated as DEP.{{cn|date=December 2015}}\n\n==Types==\n[[File:Dollop of hair gel.jpg|thumb|A dollop of hair gel.]]\n\nMany brands of hair [[gel]] in North America and the UK come in numbered variants. Higher numbered gels maintain a greater \"hold\" on hair, while lower numbers do not make the hair as stiff and in some products give the hair a wet look. A category typically referred to as \"ethnic\" gels is designed and manufactured specifically for sculpting the hair texture common to [[African Americans]]. [[Mediterranean]]s, [[Eastern Europeans]], and [[Latin American]]s are also ethnic groups who are known for using hair gel.\n\nSome forms of hair gel are marketed to consumers who want to \"spike\" their hair in the style that emerged from the [[hardcore punk]] subculture in the 1980s. Some hair gels include temporary [[Hair colouring|hair coloring]], which includes variants in unnatural colors associated with various [[subculture]]s, such as the [[Gothic fashion|goth]]s, [[rave]]rs, [[mobster]]s, and [[greaser (subculture)|greasers]].\n\n===Cationic polymers===\n[[Cation]]ic [[polymer]]s are among the main functional components of hair gel. The positive charges in the polymers causes them to stretch, making the gel more [[viscosity|viscous]]. Hair gels resist natural protein conformations and allow hair to be styled and textured, because the stretched-out polymer takes up more space than a coiled polymer and thus resists the flow of solvent molecules around it. The positive charges also bind the gel to the negatively charged [[amino acid]]s on the surface of the [[keratin]] molecules in the hair.{{cn|date=December 2015}} \n\n=== Other polymers ===\nMore complicated polymer formulas exist; i.e., a [[copolymer]] of [[vinylpyrrolidone]], [[methacrylamide]], and [[N-vinylimidazole]].{{cn|date=December 2015}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hair mousse]]\n*[[Hair wax]]\n*[[Pomade]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.bigredtoybox.com/cgi-bin/toynfo.pl?dippitydooindex|work=GoGoMag |publisher=Big Red Toybox: The Vintage Toy Encyclopedia|title=Dippity-do Setting Gel by Gillette|author=Summer Storm}}\n\n{{cosmetics}}\n[[Category:Hairdressing]]\n\n[[bn: